<subSubSection id="21A79F238D2CDEDC34576080A1AE1A40" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="C90E5761B39E155A6EB44AC71126AA78" pageNumber="657">REMARKS</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D94A1C60CF33BDEFFEAEC2D67230B206" pageNumber="657">
This species may be most closely related to 
<taxonomicName id="4058093BD08FB753E77DBC12B50E082F" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:237920" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pachycondyla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pachycondyla pilidorsalis" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="657" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pilidorsalis">P. pilidorsalis</taxonomicName>
, from which it is easily distinguished by the lack of standing hairs on mesosoma and gastral tergites 1 and 2 (excluding those arising along posterior margins of the tergites) in the queen. It is also separable from the related 
<taxonomicName id="9A92FC0E7BBE7AF667BFE60D33F4BA57" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33331" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pachycondyla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pachycondyla nigrita (Emery)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="657" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigrita">P. nigrita</taxonomicName>
by the smaller body (queen), and smaller ocelli and dark body color (male). On the other hand, in the worker caste, 
<taxonomicName id="2706592B2C896015C62D250F531F8412" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:237918" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pachycondyla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pachycondyla batak" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="657" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="batak">P. batak</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName id="87B453C67A490E865D5993C76DC441A0" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:237920" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pachycondyla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pachycondyla pilidorsalis" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="657" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pilidorsalis">P. pilidorsalis</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4E04FFFAB7307C1C4615A4DE18ED2B70" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33331" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pachycondyla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pachycondyla nigrita (Emery)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="657" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigrita">P. nigrita</taxonomicName>
only in the fewer numbers of standing hairs on mesosoma and tergites 1 and 2. This species nests in rotting wood / branches on the ground in secondary forests.
</paragraph>
